---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TopBar from '../components/TopBar.astro';
import Gallery from '../components/Gallery.astro';
import ShaderFigure from '../components/ShaderFigure.astro';
import ConceptDemo from '../components/ConceptDemo.astro';
import CircleDemo from '../components/CircleDemo.astro';
import BirthdayDemo from '../components/BirthdayDemo.astro';
import BellDemo from '../components/BellDemo.astro';
import AmFmDemo from '../components/AmFmDemo.astro';
import PrisonersDemo from '../components/PrisonersDemo.astro';
import DocDemo from '../components/DocDemo.astro';

const ideas = [
  {
    k: 'Everything is a distribution',
    d: 'A number is just a distribution with all its weight on a single point, a Dirac delta. Operators lift over random variables automatically, so X below is random and Y is random too, with no special syntax. Propagating uncertainty reads exactly like ordinary arithmetic.',
    code: 'X ~ rand::unif(-1, 1)\nY = 2 * X + 3   // Y is a distribution too',
  },
  {
    k: 'Lazy until queried: P, E, Var, Q',
    d: 'Nothing is sampled until you ask. A query runs a fast columnar Monte-Carlo pass and reports an honest estimate: the printed digits reflect the standard error, and that error propagates through arithmetic, so 4·P(C) rounds itself correctly.',
    code: 'C = X^2 + Y^2 < 1\n4 * P(C)   // ≈ 3.14',
  },
  {
    k: 'Independence is a shape',
    d: 'Put a shape on the tilde to draw a whole batch at once: ~[n] is an iid vector, ~[n, m] a matrix. A reducer collapses it back to one number, so the birthday paradox over 23 people, all 253 pairwise comparisons, fits in a single expression.',
    code: 'days ~[23] rand::unif_int(1, 365)\nP(has_duplicates(days))   // ≈ 0.51',
  },
  {
    k: 'Branches are random variables',
    d: 'When the condition is random, if c { a } else { b } builds a new random variable instead of taking a path, and each sample picks a or b on its own. That single rule hands you max, min, abs, clamps and payoffs over distributions for free.',
    code: 'RandomVariableToo = if A > B { A } else { B }   // the larger of two dice',
  },
  {
    k: 'A program is a document',
    d: 'A .noise file compiles to a live article: frontmatter names it, markdown blocks become prose, a latex block typesets itself around live values, and an input::… call renders as a slider the reader can drag, and the whole document re-runs as it moves. Every example on this site is one. Here is the program, and right below it, the document it compiles to, rendered live by the engine in your browser:',
    code: '---\ntitle: "Roll a die"\n---\nsides = input::int(min: 2, max: 100, default: 6)\n\nDie ~ rand::unif_int(1, sides)\np = P(Die == sides)\n\n```latex\nP(\\text{rolling a } ${sides}) = ${p * 100}\\%\n```',
    doc: true,
  },
];
---

<Layout>
  <TopBar />

  <article class="doc">
    <div class="measure masthead">
      <h1 class="doc-title" data-reveal>The Noise Programming Language</h1>
      <p class="doc-meta" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 60ms">
        A small, expression-based, stochastic language: write random variables like ordinary
        variables. GPU-compiled, massively parallel, blazing fast.
      </p>
      <div class="abstract" data-reveal style="--reveal-delay: 120ms">
        <p>
          <span class="abstract-label">Abstract.</span>
          In Noise, every value is a probability distribution: a number is a delta generatorl.
          Operators lift over random variables and a query such as <code class="code-inline">P(event)</code> estimates a probability by simulation.
          The result is a small language in which propagating uncertainty and running Monte-Carlo
          experiments reads like ordinary mathematics, compiled to run on the GPU and multi-core, on both native and web.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="wide" data-reveal>
      <ShaderFigure n={1} caption="the noise field this language is named for: a fractal-noise surface drawn as ink contours. Move your cursor to disturb it." />
    </div>

    <section id="tour" class="section">
      <div class="measure">
        <h2 class="sec" data-reveal>Keep scrolling</h2>
        <p data-reveal>
          The best way to learn a language is to watch it unfold in front of you, so keep scrolling.
          Six small programs, each one idea past the last, animate as you read them, then run for real
          on the compiled engine in your browser. It has a touch of magic to it, because every
          variable here is a whole wave of possibility, and a query is what collapses it to a single
          number.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="tour-item"><div class="wide"><ConceptDemo /></div></div>
      <div class="tour-item"><div class="wide"><CircleDemo /></div></div>
      <div class="tour-item"><div class="wide"><BirthdayDemo /></div></div>
      <div class="tour-item"><div class="wide"><BellDemo /></div></div>
      <div class="tour-item"><div class="wide"><AmFmDemo /></div></div>
      <div class="tour-item"><div class="wide"><PrisonersDemo /></div></div>
    </section>

    <section id="examples" class="section">
      <div class="measure">
        <h2 class="sec" data-reveal>Examples</h2>
        <p data-reveal>
          A catalogue of short programs, each a Monte-Carlo experiment with a known closed form, so
          the printed answer can be checked. Open any one in the
          <a href="/play">playground</a> to run and edit it on the real Noise compiler, built to
          WebAssembly and running in your browser. Each program gets its own shareable link.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="wide" data-reveal>
        <Gallery />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="ideas" class="section">
      <div class="measure">
        <h2 class="sec" data-reveal>How it works</h2>
        <p data-reveal>
          Noise is small by design. Everything above is built from a handful of ideas.
        </p>

        {ideas.map((i) => (
          <div class="subsec-block">
            <h3 class="subsec" data-reveal>{i.k}</h3>
            <p data-reveal>{i.d}</p>
            <pre class="listing" data-reveal><code>{i.code}</code></pre>
            {i.doc && <DocDemo code={i.code} />}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="performance" class="section">
      <div class="measure">
        <h2 class="sec" data-reveal>Performance</h2>
        <p data-reveal>
          Almost every Noise program ends in “evaluate this expression over a few million random
          draws.” That loop is compiled, not interpreted. A query like
          <code class="code-inline">P(...)</code> is secretly a compute shader with a map/reduce
          attached: one pure kernel evaluated over millions of independent lanes, then folded down
          to a single number. You never write that shader. The <code class="code-inline">~</code>
          bindings and the distribution constructors build a graph IR of it under the hood.
        </p>
        <p data-reveal>
          The engine then picks how to run each query, like a SQL query planner picks an execution
          plan: a cost model keeps small queries on the vectorized columnar interpreter, fans
          medium ones out across every core with a work-stealing reducer, and compiles the heavy
          ones into a single fused WGSL compute shader for the GPU, on native and in the browser
          through WebGPU. Switching paths can only ever change the speed, because the draws are
          bit-identical on every backend.
        </p>
        <p data-reveal>
          So you write a one-line <code class="code-inline">P(...)</code> and get an expert kernel
          for free. It is built from a stack of techniques, each with its own measured win:
        </p>
        <ul class="perf-techniques" data-reveal>
          <li>
            <b>Kernel fusion:</b> the codegen backends emit one loop that draws its sources, computes
            the whole expression in registers, and stores only the result, so the interpreter's
            intermediate memory traffic disappears.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Graph simplification:</b> constant folding, finite-safe algebraic identities, and
            common-subexpression elimination shrink the DAG before any code is generated (so
            <code class="code-inline">X + X</code> is one draw, not two).
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Counter-based RNG (squares64):</b> inlined straight into the kernel, and stateless
            by construction. A draw is a pure function of (seed, lane, source), so any slice of the
            sample space can run on any core or any GPU thread and still land bit-identical. The
            generator is certified, too: it passes a seven-test statistical battery and a 1&nbsp;TB
            <a href="https://pracrand.sourceforge.net/">PractRand</a> run over the engine's exact
            draw stream with zero anomalies.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Inlined transcendentals:</b> <code class="code-inline">ln</code>/<code class="code-inline">sin</code>/<code class="code-inline">cos</code>
            (the heart of <code class="code-inline">normal</code>, <code class="code-inline">exp</code>,
            and signals) become straight-line polynomial approximations that roughly double
            transcendental-bound kernels and skip a per-draw crossing of the JS boundary in the
            browser. On the GPU they map to the hardware transcendental units, so they run super fast.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>GPU dispatch:</b> a heavy query lowers to a WGSL compute shader. Array draws and
            <code class="code-inline">for</code> loops emit as real loops rather than unrolling,
            permutations and rotations run natively per lane, and one dispatch covers millions of
            lanes. Thanks to <a href="https://wgpu.rs/">wgpu</a>, the one emitter reaches Metal,
            Vulkan, and DirectX&nbsp;12 natively and WebGPU in the browser, so there is a single
            GPU backend to maintain instead of one per platform.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Columnar batches:</b> the interpreter runs 1024 lanes through one instruction at a
            time, a tight, cache-friendly, auto-vectorizing pass over contiguous
            <code class="code-inline">f32</code> lanes (aggregation stays <code class="code-inline">f64</code>).
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Vectorized power-sum reduction:</b> moments accumulate as raw power sums across eight
            unrolled lanes with no per-element divide. That is ~9.5× faster than a streaming Welford
            update, and it turns the reduction from the ceiling into a rounding error.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Deterministic multicore:</b> sampling fans out with a work-stealing loop whose
            per-chunk accumulators merge as an exactly-associative monoid, so the answer is
            bit-identical regardless of thread count, and reproducible from a seed.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>Profitability gate:</b> a cost model sends a query to the GPU (or emits a fused
            kernel) only where it beats the vectorized interpreter, so codegen can change the speed
            but never lose. Anything a backend can't lower falls back to the interpreter, which is
            correct and a bit slower.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p data-reveal>The payoff, measured on a 14-core M4 Pro:</p>
        <ul class="perf-stats" data-reveal>
          <li>
            <b>~5.8 billion</b> samples/sec (π Monte&nbsp;Carlo, generate + reduce, all cores), and
            it scales <b>~9.6×</b> from one core to all of them.
          </li>
          <li>
            The GPU backend runs the full example corpus <b>~4.2×</b> faster end to end than the
            interpreter, and the heaviest simulations gain far more: the random-rotation
            quantization study drops from 1474&nbsp;ms to <b>55&nbsp;ms (~26×)</b> and the
            100-prisoners simulation from 59&nbsp;ms to <b>2.8&nbsp;ms (~21×)</b>, with the same
            seeds and the same answers.
          </li>
          <li>
            On GPU-shaped work it beats hand-written CPU code outright: a 100-million-draw normal
            kernel takes 96&nbsp;ms on a hand-tuned multicore CPU implementation and
            <b>5&nbsp;ms</b> as a single GPU dispatch.
          </li>
          <li>
            The browser gets the same treatment: the emitted WASM kernel runs the fused loop at
            <b>~0.5–0.75×</b> of native codegen, and WebGPU runs the heavy compute shaders in the
            playground, so dragging a slider on the heaviest example re-runs the whole document in
            about <b>90&nbsp;ms</b> where the CPU path took 14 seconds.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p data-reveal>
          The full write-up, with the benchmark tables behind each number, is in
          <a href="https://github.com/manucorporat/noise-lang/blob/master/PERF.md">PERF.md</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="author" class="section">
      <div class="measure">
        <h2 class="sec" data-reveal>About the creator</h2>

        <div class="author" data-reveal>
          <figure class="author-portrait">
            <picture>
              <source srcset="/manu.webp" type="image/webp" />
              <img
                src="/manu.jpg"
                width="900"
                height="934"
                loading="lazy"
                decoding="async"
                alt="Manu Martínez-Almeida"
              />
            </picture>
            <figcaption>Manu Martínez-Almeida</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <div class="author-body">
            <p class="author-lede">
              <a href="https://manualmeida.dev/"><span class="author-name">Manu Mtz.-Almeida.</span></a>
              Creator of <a href="https://github.com/gin-gonic/gin">Gin</a>, core contributor to <a href="https://ionicframework.com/">Ionic</a>,
              <a href="https://stenciljs.com/">Stencil</a> and <a href="https://qwik.dev/">Qwik</a>. Principal engineer at
              <a href="https://www.builder.io/">Builder.io</a>, working on compilers,
              high-performance systems, and AI agents.
            </p>
            <p>
              I started Noise nine years ago and never quite finished it. The idea grew out of
              my telecommunications degree, a world of signals, noise, and probability, where
              I kept wishing for a language that could express uncertainty as naturally as it
              expresses arithmetic. This is that wish.
            </p>
            <p class="author-links">
              <a href="https://github.com/manucorporat">github.com/manucorporat</a>
              <span class="author-sep">·</span>
              <a href="https://x.com/manucorporat">x.com/manucorporat</a>
              <span class="author-sep">·</span>
              <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/manumartinez-almeida">linkedin</a>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="doc-footer measure">
      <hr />
      <p class="muted" id="footer-version">noise~lang · running on WebAssembly.</p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .doc { counter-reset: section; padding: 2.5rem 0 1rem; }

  .masthead { padding-top: 1.5rem; }
  .doc-title {
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 3.1rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .doc-meta { color: var(--ink-dim); font-size: 1.05rem; margin: 0 0 1.6rem; font-style: italic; }
  .abstract {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--rule);
    padding: 0.1rem 0 0.1rem 1.2rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .abstract p { margin: 0; font-size: 1.02rem; color: #2c2a24; }
  .abstract-label { font-weight: 700; }

  .section { padding: 2.5rem 0; }

  /* numbered sections + subsections, paper-style */
  .sec {
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2rem);
    margin: 0 0 0.8rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.35rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .tour-item { margin-top: 3.5rem; }
  .tour-item .demo-title { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .subsec-block { margin-top: 2rem; }
  .subsec { font-size: 1.25rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }

  /* performance: techniques (named) + headline stats (numeric) */
  .perf-techniques { margin: 1.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .perf-techniques li { margin: 0.6rem 0; line-height: 1.62; }
  .perf-techniques b { font-weight: 700; color: var(--ink); }

  .perf-stats { margin: 1.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .perf-stats li { margin: 0.5rem 0; line-height: 1.6; }
  .perf-stats b { font-family: var(--mono); font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent); }

  /* code listing on the page */
  .listing {
    background: var(--paper-2);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    overflow-x: auto;
    white-space: pre;
    color: #2c2a24;
  }

  .doc-footer { padding-bottom: 3rem; }
  .doc-footer p { font-size: 0.92rem; }

  /* about the author: a journal-style author note, typeset like the end of a paper */
  .author {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.6rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    margin-top: 0.6rem;
  }
  .author-portrait {
    flex: 0 0 auto;
    width: 168px;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .author-portrait img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-radius: 3px;
    background: var(--paper-2);
    /* a faint warm cast so the photo sits in the cream palette rather than on top of it */
    filter: saturate(0.92) contrast(1.02);
  }
  .author-portrait figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink-dim);
    text-align: center;
  }
  .author-body { flex: 1 1 auto; min-width: 0; }
  .author-body > p { margin: 0 0 0.85rem; }
  .author-body > p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .author-lede { color: #2c2a24; }
  /* small-caps name, the way an author byline is set in a journal */
  .author-name {
    font-weight: 700;
    font-variant: small-caps;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    margin-right: 0.15em;
  }
  .author-links {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    color: var(--ink-dim);
    padding-top: 0.3rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .author-sep { color: var(--ink-faint); margin: 0 0.5em; }

  @media (max-width: 560px) {
    .author { flex-direction: column; gap: 1.1rem; }
    .author-portrait { width: 140px; align-self: flex-start; }
    .author-portrait figcaption { text-align: left; }
  }
</style>

<script>
  import { noiseVersion } from '../lib/noise';
  noiseVersion()
    .then((v) => {
      const el = document.getElementById('footer-version');
      if (el) el.textContent = `noise~lang v${v} · running on WebAssembly.`;
    })
    .catch(() => {});
</script>
